		<h3>The Deal</h3>
		<p>
		The deck is shuffled by the dealer and cut by the player to the right of the dealer.
		The dealer then deals one card to every player starting with the player to the dealer’s
		left until there are no cards left. Each player should have 13 cards. After a round is
		completed the next dealer is the player to the left of the previous dealer.
		</p>

		<h3>Order of Play</h3>
		<p>
		Each round in Spades consists of two parts: the bid and taking books. At the start of every
		round, immediately after dealing, the dealer’s team begins the bid by deciding amongst one
		another how many books they believe they can take that round. After they have finalized their
		bid the other team decided on their bid. While the two partners can talk during this phase 
		they may not give details about which cards they have in their hand. The players are only 
		allowed to say how many books they can take. Four books is the minimum bid for a team, and 
		no team may bid nine. The sum of both teams' bids must be at least ten, if the sum of both teams'
		bids is less than ten, the result is a misdeal. Once both teams have bid, the score keeper 
		marks down their bids and the game progresses to the next phase.
		</p>

		<div class="alert alert-primary" role="alert">
