  		<h5>NOTE: Going Nil</h5>
			</div>
			<div id="panel">
		<p class="note">There is one exception to the minimum bid of four books rule. If a team wished they can declare 
		that they are "going nil" which means they bid zero books. If they succeed in losing every single 
		book they earn 100 points. If they take even one book they lose 100 points.</p>
		</div>
		</div>

		<p>
		After the bidding phase each player lays a card down in clockwise order, beginning with the 
		player to the left of the dealer. Once every player has played a card the player with the 
		highest card collects the group of four cards and claims it for their team, this is called 
		a book. The player who won the previous book become the lead player and begins the next book.
		All players must play a card of the same suit as the card played by the lead player, unless 
		they have no cards of that suit. A spade of any value will take any value card of the lead suit.
		Any other suit (not spades or the lead suit) will lose to any value card of the lead suit or 
		any spade. If a player is out of the lead suit and takes a book with a spade it is called 
		"cutting". Spades cannot be led until a spade has been used to cut on a previous book that round. 
		If a player is caught playing a off-suit card (a card that is not the lead suit) while they 
		still have cards of the lead suit in their hand, their team is deducted 100 points.
		</p>
		
		<h3>Scoring</h3>
		<p>
		After each round, each team totals up their books. If a team takes the same amount or more than
		their bid, they earn 10 points for every book they bid. For every book they take that is more 
		than their bid they earn a bag. Each time a team earns 10 bags they are deducted 100 points. If 
		a team does not earn as many books as they bid they are “set” and they lose 10 points for every 
		book they bid. If a team is set twice in a row or three times in a game they lose the game. The 
		first team to reach 500 points wins.
 		</p>

		<h3>Scoring Example</h3>
		<p>
		Team A bids 6 books and Team B bids 6 books. If Team A ends up taking 8 books, they would get 
		60 points, ten for each books bid, and 2 bags, one for each additional book. Team B only took 5 
		which means they are set and they lose 60 points, 10 for each book they bid.
		</p>
		
